defaultWhat types of CCS technology are currently being developed and how do they differ from one another? default3.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default There are two potential CCS techniques that could be applic
defaultable for capturing CO
default2
default from cement manufacture: Post-Combustion Capture and Oxy-Combustion Capture. Pre-Combustion capture is disregarded on the basis that it would only address the fuel part of the CO
default2
default emission (only ~40% of the total emission from cement manufacture comes from fuel burning).
default3.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultPost combustion capture is an ‘end-of-pipe’ technology that has the advantage of being able to be retrofitted to existing plant if space allows.
default3.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultIt works by ‘scr
defaultubbing’ the exhaust gases with a solvent (most likely an amine), the solvent is then regenerated using steam and the high concentration CO
default2
default gas is compressed for transport. 
defaultThese technologies also have significant electricity
default 
defaultdemands. These demands are so 
defaultsignificant that additional power and steam requirements
default 
defaultwould probably need to
default be supplied by the addition of a
default Combined Heat and Power (CHP) plant.
default3.4.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultThe key constraints for this option are: 
defaultSulphur dioxide (
defaultSO
default2
default)
default, 
defaultOxides of Nitr
defaulto
defaultgen (
defaultNOx
default)
default in the flue gas (potential interference with the 
defaultCO
default2
default 
defaultabsorption
default by the amine
default); space for the capture and compression equipment; availability of steam for amine regeneration. 
default3.5.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultAll the major technical issues could, potentially, be addressed using existing 
defaulttechnology but the main barrier to its application is the cost 
defaultof deploying these technologies.
default3.6.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe cost per tonne of CO
default2
default emissions avoided is substantially higher than using oxy-combustion, mainly due to the large capital costs of the Combined Heat and Power plant and the flue gas desulphurization, (FGD) plant.
default3.7.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultOxy-combustion CO
default2
default-capture is at an earlier stage of developme
defaultnt than post-combustion and its use would require the fundamental re-design of a cement plant.
default3.8.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultMany technical issues centre on burning the raw materials in an oxygen rich environment either in the 
defaultkiln 
defaultprecalciner or potentially in the kiln itself. Resear
defaultch on this and how product formation may be affected by high CO
default2
default concentrations is also needed.
default3.9.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultHowever, the predicted cost per tonne of CO
default2
default emissions avoided is about 40% of that for post-combustion capture.  
default3.10.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
