default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat contribution could CCS make towards the UK’s decarbonisation targets? Are the UK Government’s defaultexpectations reasonable in this regard?default4.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK Government is ambitious with its rhetoric around carbon capture but very unambitious with its support for the delivery of CCS, particularly in industry.
default4.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultClimate change is very important to the cement industry 
defaultfor two key reasons; firstly, cement production releases carbon dioxide; and secondly, cement concrete products are needed to mitigate against climate change by producing thermally efficient high mass buildings and because cement concrete products will hel
defaultp society adapt to the effects of global warming e.g. drainage and flood defence.
default As such society will always need to consume cement and concrete. It is therefore important that the cement industry addresses its CO
default2
default footprint. MPA Cement is the 
defaultfirst 
defaultnatio
defaultnal cement association to outline its contribution to society’s decarbonation pathway to 2050.
default 
default4.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe UK cement industry has published its ‘Greenhouse gas strategy to 2050’
default. Outlining an ambitious target of -81%  GHG emissions  by 2050, against 1990, (the 
defaultKyoto Protocol baseline year), the UK cement industry has set out for the first time the actions they, and others, need to take to exceed the UK Government’s own -80% aim. Government support to assist and accelerate the delivery of this strategy is noticea
defaultbly absent and without such support the maximum ambition of an 81% decarbonisation of UK cement production by 2050 may not be delivered.
default The UK cement industry roadmap demonstrates that without CCS the decarbonisation by 2050 
defaultof 
default62%
default is all that could be po
defaultssible
default.
