default6.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhat are the main barriers (e.g. economic, political, regulatory, scientific and social) to developing large-scale integrated CCS projects in the UK and internationally? How can they be overcome? default6.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default defaultThe technical 
defaultchallenges of CCS in the cement are not insurmountable but the financial barriers are considerable.
default6.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default defaultExhaust gas from a cement kiln contains about 25% CO
default2
default – appreciably higher than in coal fired power generation (about 14%).  Although the concentration of 
defaultCO
default2
default in the exhaust gas makes cement CO
default2
default capture an attractive proposition when compared to power generation, economies of scale make it more expensive. A single 2GW coal fired power station emits approximately the same amount of CO
default2
default as the whole of the UK 
defaultcement industry.
default6.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default IEA GHG
default 
defaulthave estimated that a post-combustion capture fitted cement plant could cost around €558m (more than twice the cost of a non-CCS equivalent) but providing a potential emissions avoided efficiency  of 77%. An equivalent output oxy
default-combustion plant, however, could cost €327m (25% more expensive than the non-CCS plant) but at an emissions avoided rate of 52%.
default6.4.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultOperational costs are potentially considerable too; they double for the post-combustion option and increase by 25% for oxy-co
defaultmbustion compared to non-CCS plant.
default6.5.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultAlthough these costs make the oxy-combustion plant comparatively attractive it must be noted that oxy-combustion is at a much earlier stage of development compared to post combustion and for cement making it would radic
defaultally change the design and operation of the kiln.
default6.6.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
default              
defaultThe work of the British Geological Survey has improved the knowledge of potential storage sites around the UK but regulatory controls and legal liabilities are at the early stages of development. It is un
defaultlikely that the cement industry will get too involved in storage sites and will look to third parties for the development of this important part of the CCS chain.
default6.7.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe volumes of CO
default2
default generated by individual cement installations are too small to warrant dedicated pipelines connected to either potential off-shore or on-shore storage sites. Consequently, a strategic CO
default2
default pipeline infrastructure is needed for high volume emitters in the po
defaultwer generation sector with connection nodes for smaller industrial emitters. Such a project 
defaulthas to be centrally funded by Government
default. Until a strategic infrastructure pipeline network is in place this represents a significant barrier to CCS deployment in t
defaulthe non-generation sectors. 
default6.8.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default Finally, industrial processes are much more vulnerable to the economic cycle than power generators that have a captive non-mobile market in the domestic sector where they are able to pass on the cost of CCS to the consumer with
defaultout much risk. Industrial operator output is influenced by the economic cycle, for example the UK cement market it around 35% lower than pre-recession levels and the sector does not have the ability to pass on the cost of CCS to its consumers. 
default7.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultAre there adefaultny safety issues associated with capturing, transporting and storing carbon dioxide? How could they be overcome? Who should have responsibility for ensuring these activities are safe? default7.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultMPA does not envisage that the safety issues associated with carbon cap
defaultture in the cement industry would be any greater than in any other industrial or power CCS project. 
default7.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default The UK has a good record of regulating industrial processes and CCS should be no different
default, although effort might be needed to gain public acceptance of C
defaultCS.
